  <Fragment slot="extra-sections">
    <section>
      <h2>How to fix an AeroPress recipe that tastes off</h2>
      <p>
        If the cup tastes <strong>sour</strong>, that usually means the water did not pull enough flavor out of the coffee. In coffee-speak that is under-extraction,
        but the fix is simple. Grind a little finer, steep a little longer, or raise the water temperature a touch. Start with one change, not three.
      </p>
      <p>
        If the cup tastes <strong>bitter</strong>, hollow, or kind of harsh, back off instead. Go a little coarser, shorten the steep, or stop pressing right when you hear the hiss.
        Darker roasts especially go from chocolatey to rough fast if you overdo the heat or the contact time.
      </p>
      <p>
        If the cup tastes <strong>muddy</strong>, think filter and grinder before you chase another random recipe. Paper filters clean up the finish. A better burr grinder makes the grounds more even,
        so the brew stops tasting like bitter dust mixed with sour pebbles. If you want help on that part, our <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-grind-size.html">best AeroPress grind size guide</a>
        and <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-coffee-ratio.html">best AeroPress coffee ratio guide</a> are the next pages to read.
      </p>
      <p>
        The biggest mistake is changing everything at once. Keep the dose steady. Keep the water amount steady. Then adjust a single variable and taste again.
        It sounds boring. It is also how you stop wasting beans and start getting good cups on purpose.
      </p>
    </section>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="buying-guide">
    <BuyingGuideSection>
      <h2 id="buying-guide">What to buy for more consistency</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Start with the brewer first.</strong> If you are new, the standard AeroPress Original is enough. It lets you learn what grind size, ratio, and water temperature do without hiding the result.
        That matters because the best recipe is not just the tastiest one. It is the one that teaches you what changed in the cup.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Add a grinder before you add fancy accessories.</strong> A burr grinder just means the coffee comes out more even instead of breaking into random dust and boulders.
        That one upgrade changes AeroPress more than most people expect. If you want a compact manual option, the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0833SDN8M/ref=nosim?tag=coffee-site-20" rel="nofollow sponsored noopener" target="_blank">TIMEMORE Chestnut C2</a>
        is a solid place to start because it travels well and gives you cleaner, more predictable cups.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Buy a flow-control accessory only if you know what problem you are solving.</strong> If you want more body, longer immersion, or stronger bypass brews,
        a flow-control cap or Prismo makes sense. If you are already happy with the standard recipe, you do not need extra gear just because it exists.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Paper filters are the cheapest meaningful upgrade.</strong> They are especially worth it if you lean toward light roasts or just hate gritty cups.
        That is a small spend with a very obvious payoff in the mug.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>A small scale helps more than people think.</strong> AeroPress is forgiving, but it still rewards repeatable ratios. Once your dose drifts from 15 grams to 17,
        or your water swings from 220 grams to 260, the recipe is not really the same recipe anymore. A tiny scale keeps your good cup from turning into a happy accident.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Travel is its own decision tree.</strong> If your AeroPress mostly leaves the house, buy for convenience first. The AeroPress Go keeps the workflow tight,
        and that usually matters more than chasing tiny flavor gains with a bulky setup you stop carrying after a week.
      </p>

      <h3>Useful next reads</h3>
      <p>
        <CtaButton href="/posts/best-aeropress-brewing-method.html" variant="secondary">Best AeroPress Brewing Method</CtaButton>
